1274
02:37:25,555 --> 02:37:28,397
[SPEAKER_20]: whatever four degree band of whatever it is.

1275
02:37:29,258 --> 02:37:31,980
[SPEAKER_20]: We do that across the campus I work at.

1276
02:37:32,721 --> 02:37:43,049
[SPEAKER_20]: Every single building has the same temperature standards and every room has two degrees plus or minus a set temperature.

1277
02:37:43,069 --> 02:37:47,093
[SPEAKER_20]: And it's kind of control within a bracket.

1278
02:37:48,023 --> 02:38:00,495
[SPEAKER_20]: Um, and it's understanding, um, that this building, the envelope will be so much better than, um, the envelope you have now.

1279
02:38:01,296 --> 02:38:03,878
[SPEAKER_20]: Anything will be better than the envelope you have now.

1280
02:38:03,898 --> 02:38:03,938
[SPEAKER_20]: Um,

1281
02:38:06,661 --> 02:38:15,790
[SPEAKER_20]: and understanding that a lot of times, if you don't have that kind of bracket, your building will start to fight against each other.

1282
02:38:15,810 --> 02:38:19,893
[SPEAKER_20]: And you'll have one room next to another room, and those two rooms will be fighting against each other.

1283
02:38:19,953 --> 02:38:27,660
[SPEAKER_20]: So I just want to caution against the desire to have whatever temperature you want and just kind of put that out there.

1284
02:38:29,142 --> 02:38:30,423
[SPEAKER_20]: So that's all.

1285
02:38:31,866 --> 02:38:44,812
[SPEAKER_17]: Yeah, so typically, just bouncing off of that, that is what we do for a lot of our schools is we give the teachers local controllability, but it's just within a certain few degree range.

1286
02:38:46,313 --> 02:38:55,738
[SPEAKER_17]: And then there's an overall schedule that's controlled by the facilities team that sets all the classrooms back to a typical school schedule.

1287
02:38:56,939 --> 02:39:08,187
[SPEAKER_17]: so that if some teachers bump up the temperature by a few degrees during the school day and then they forget to set it back after hours, the system will reset itself to save on energy.

1288
02:39:08,788 --> 02:39:15,173
[SPEAKER_17]: So that is something that we have done at other schools that's been liked by everyone.

1289
02:39:17,855 --> 02:39:18,896
[SPEAKER_26]: Jenny, do you want to chime in?

1290
02:39:23,695 --> 02:39:33,337
[SPEAKER_14]: I was actually going to ask the project team to provide us some guidance about best practice in large commercial and municipal buildings.

1291
02:39:33,377 --> 02:39:42,259
[SPEAKER_14]: It's mind-blowing to me that anybody would allow complete control in a room-by-room basis.

1292
02:39:42,399 --> 02:39:45,299
[SPEAKER_14]: I didn't think that happened anymore.

1293
02:39:45,419 --> 02:39:47,620
[SPEAKER_14]: So if there are some best practices out there,

1294
02:39:50,035 --> 02:40:17,980
[SPEAKER_14]: I think I would appreciate knowing what they are so that we can communicate effectively to teachers who have legitimately been in very terrible heat and climate conditions for a really long time, like A, why this is going to be better, and B, why there are many solutions to this that aren't sort of unfettered control of the temperature, because I think

1295
02:40:18,517 --> 02:40:25,800
[SPEAKER_14]: you know, it doesn't, in that kind of a model, it would not take much to be in a like budget crisis halfway through the year.

1296
02:40:25,960 --> 02:40:33,362
[SPEAKER_14]: Like, and we can't, we obviously have to protect against those kinds of unforeseen circumstances too.

1297
02:40:33,422 --> 02:40:46,927
